/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F59%2Fa6%2F3551030a4d5bbc93e62edaa53dd4%2Fgettyimages-2226807556.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F59%2Fa6%2F3551030a4d5bbc93e62edaa53dd4%2Fgettyimages-2226807556.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4000x2250+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F59%2Fa6%2F3551030a4d5bbc93e62edaa53dd4%2Fgettyimages-2226807556.jpg" class="img" alt="A Starbucks coffee shop in New York on Monday, July 28, 2025. Starbucks Corp. is closing stores and laying off 900 corporate employees as part of a turnaround strategy." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 A Starbucks coffee shop in New York on Monday, July 28, 2025. Starbucks Corp. is closing stores and laying off 900 corporate employees as part of a turnaround strategy.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Bloomberg/Bloomberg via Getty Images/Bloomberg                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ol class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;Starbucks &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/09/25/nx-s1-5553386/starbucks-closes-stores-cuts-900-jobs" target="_blank"&gt;intends to eliminate 900 corporate jobs&lt;/a&gt; and close some of its stores in the U.S. and Canada as the company approaches the one-year mark of its turnaround plan.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Amazon has agreed to &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/09/25/nx-s1-5551026/amazon-prime-lawsuit-ftc-settlement" target="_blank"&gt;pay $2.5 billion to settle a landmark case&lt;/a&gt; over its Prime membership program. The U.S. government claimed the company made it difficult for millions of people to cancel subscriptions.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Squirrels may be cute, but fair warning, they can attack. Residents in Marin County, Calif., learned this the hard way when at least three people from one neighborhood were sent to the hospital after being &lt;a href="https://www.kqed.org/news/12057604/squirrels-gone-wild-marin-county-attack-squirrel-sends-at-least-3-to-the-er" target="_blank"&gt;attacked by one squirrel&lt;/a&gt;. (via &lt;a href="https://www.kqed.org/" target="_blank"&gt;KQED&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This newsletter was edited by &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/people/859721331/suzanne-nuyen"target="_blank"   &gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Suzanne Nuyen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
